Date: Fri 25 Jan 2013
Source: Ozarks First [edited]
http://ozarksfirst.com/fulltext?nxd_id=758932


White-nose syndrome confirmed in bat at Missouri cave
-----------------------------------------------------
Missouri State Parks has received confirmation that a bat found in the entrance of Onondaga Cave at Onondaga Cave State Park in Crawford County has tested positive with white-nose syndrome(WNS).

WNS spreads mainly through bat-to-bat contact and has not been found to infect people, pets or livestock but is harmful or lethal to hibernating bats. The fungus that causes WNS may be inadvertently carried between caves by humans through clothing and equipment.

The U.S. Geological Survey's National Wildlife Health Center confirmed the bat had the disease described as a white fungus, or _Geomyces destructans_, which is typically found on the faces and wings of infected bats.

Education is an important aspect of the overall effort to manage WNS and part of the state park system mission. In 2010, Missouri State Parks staff began educating and screening visitors before each cave tour to help minimize risks to bats.

While WNS is mainly transmitted bat to bat, scientists believe that the fungus can be carried on clothing, footwear and caving gear. Therefore, staff will require visitors to wear only clothing and bring equipment that has not been in another cave before. In addition, staff took action to protect the bats from disturbance while hibernating in caves and adjusted the touring season to avoid disturbing the bats in fall and spring when they are gathering for, or preparing to leave, hibernation.

Missouri State Parks has a dual responsibility of preserving nature while providing opportunities for people to enjoy our state parks. Nearly 20 000 people visit Onondaga Cave every year.

Staff will continue to provide information and require additional measures for visitors to follow both before and after a cave tour when the cave opens for the tour season to help reduce the risk of cave-to-cave transmission of the fungus.

The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service has indicated that WNS has killed at least 5.5 million cave-dwelling bats since the disease was 1st detected in New York in 2006. Signs of the disease have spread to 21 states and the disease has been confirmed in 19 states and 4 Canadian provinces. Signs of the disease in Missouri were 1st discovered in 2010.

Today, signs of the disease or the fungus have been confirmed in 15 bats from caves in Pike, Shannon, Lincoln, Perry, Washington and now Crawford counties.

More information on WNS is available at http://www.whitenosesyndrome.org. For more information on Missouri State Parks and Onondaga Cave State Park, visit the Web at http://www.mostateparks.com. Missouri State Parks is a division of the Missouri Department of Natural Resources.

